solution.p:
Now all the ways to distribute the 9 units to the four y_i variables can be found using stars and bars, specifically 9 stars and 3 bars, so {12 \choose 9} ways. But this includes the ways that one or more y_i variables can be assigned more than 3 units. So subtract using PIE to get

\displaystyle{                {12 \choose 3} -\left( {4\choose 1} {7 \choose 3}-{4\choose 2} {2 \choose 3} + \dots \right)
              }

